Utterances.UttText: Sub: Mr.
Cage is a 47 yo male with a history of HTN who presents with progressing chest pain over the past 4 months.

Phrases.PhraseText: a 47 yo male with a history of HTN

Utterances.UttText: 3 days ago, he was carrying groceries and had sudden-onset deeply achy, heavy chest pain, rated 7/10, with light headedness that caused him to drop his groceries.

Phrases.PhraseText: sudden-onset deeply achy, heavy chest pain,

Utterances.UttText: After he sat in the car for 5-10 minutes, the pain subsided on its own.
No LOC.
Similar events have happened over the past 4 months while exerting himself, though the most recent episode was the most severe.
He also noted that he occasionally experiences a pressure sensation in his chest after eating a big lunch that lasts 3-5 minutes and subsides on his own.

Phrases.PhraseText: a pressure sensation in his chest

Utterances.UttText: There are no specific foods that trigger this pain.
These events have been going on for about 1 year.
No dyspnea, diaphoresis, headaches, anxiety, vision changes.
ROS: as per HPI, all other systems reviewed and were negative.
Meds: chlorthalidone (25 mg daily), lisinopril (10 mg daily) Allergies: NKDA PMH: hypertension (diagnosed 5 years ago) No surgeries FH: dad had MI at age 40 and was diagnosed with CAD, is s/p CABG.

MappingCandidates.CandidatePreferred: Life Expectancy Less than Five Years

Utterances.UttText: Mom has HTN, DM II, died of PE SH: works at Capital 1 in branding.
Smokes 1 ppd cigarettes x 20 years.

MappingCandidates.CandidatePreferred: Life Expectancy Greater than Twenty Years

Utterances.UttText: Drinks 2-3 glasses of wine 2x/week.
No recreational drugs.
Obj: VS: T 98 P 85 R 14 BP 150/92 Exam: General: no acute distress, appears nervous Cardio: RRR, no murmurs/rubs/gallops, PMI normal, radial pulses 2+ Resp: nonlabored breathing  Assessment: Mr.
Cage is 47 yo M with a history of HTN who presents with progressive chest pain that occurs in the setting of exertion that subsides with rest.

Phrases.PhraseText: 47 yo M with a history of HTN
occurs in the setting of exertion

Utterances.UttText: Family history is notable for HTN, MI at age 40, and CAD.
Cardiac exam is within normal limits.
Most likely diagnosis is angina given chest pain with exertion that subsides with rest.

Phrases.PhraseText: angina given chest pain with exertion

Utterances.UttText: Other diagnoses include MI and aortic dissection  Plan ekg stress test
